    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Too Much Complaining About Real Estate Taxes</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Laurie Crosse letter on April 15 article says she has no sympathy for people who complain about high real estate taxes</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I have no sympathy for Joe Greco or Jim Isaacs or their families (''Alternative Tax Hits Home the Hardest,'' April 15).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I have no sympathy for Joe Greco or Jim Isaacs or their families (''Alternative Tax Hits Home the Hardest,'' April 15).</p>
        <p>Anyone who can pay $19,000 annually in real estate taxes who cannot acknowledge that he is wealthy is either sorrowfully deluded or incredibly selfish, and any politician who calls the tax ''exorbitant'' is just pandering to her wealthy constituents.</p>
        <p>I live in wealthy Dix Hills, pay five-figure real estate taxes and wake up every morning thanking God for my good fortune and praying for the people around New York, America and the world who have no work, no potable water, no food, no shelter. If doubling my taxes took away these tragedies I would willingly pay them.</p>
        <p>Only in America do people have the audacity to move into a mini-mansion one week and complain that taxes are overburdening their ''decent salary'' the next.</p>
        <p>Laurie Crosse  Dix Hills</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
